##Art School exam postponed, art training institutions to find a way out

Offline enrollment channel blocked, has been art training institutions began to attach importance to online enrollment.

February is a key time for art examinees to prepare for the university entrance examination, but this year, many students and art exam training institutions have to adjust their plans because of the epidemic of new coronavirus pneumonia.

On January 23, the China Central Academy of Fine Arts announced that it was postponing the professional exams scheduled for February 22 to 23, and that the school would reschedule the exams in light of the development of the epidemic. Also postponing professional examinations are the Central Academy of Drama, the Fine Arts College of Tsinghua University, the Beijing Film Academy and many other art schools. According to the Beijing Municipal Education Commission, in 2020, a total of 46 universities in Beijing organized special types of tests, such as art classes and high-level art troupes, most of which have yet to organize examinations.

The Art exam consists of the provincial exams from December to January, and the exams are held again from February to March, as art students prepare for the exams. After finishing the school exam, they also need to cram for the cultural courses, in order to face the college entrance exam. After the postponement of the school examination, the art examinees have to prepare for both the professional courses and the cultural courses.

"It's hard to go back and concentrate on studying for the cultural course without the professional exam finished, " Zhang Qiong, an art candidate, told interface education.

On the other hand, colleges and universities have higher and higher requirements for art students to take the college entrance examination. According to the basic requirements for admission to special types of students issued by the Ministry of Education over the years, in 2018 and before, the requirements for the admission control scores of art candidates in the college entrance examination for Culture classes shall not be lower than 65 percent of the local second-tier, and in 2019 it has been raised to more than 70 percent. In addition, colleges and universities are not allowed to lower the minimum admission score set for the first time in order to complete the enrollment plan.

"We can't catch up on either side now, " said Wang Fang, an art candidate. She believes that most secondary schools are now moving online, making it harder for students who haven't been exposed to the arts for a long time to keep up.

Zhang Chong, a teacher at the Communication University of China, believes that students with middle grades are the most vulnerable to the rising standards for admission to cultural courses.

"neither the 'overachievers' nor the 'underachievers' will be disturbed by the external environment, and students in the middle will lack supervision or become lazy, and cultural classes will most likely fail to meet the standards, " he told interface education, some colleges and universities even set the score line, the actual number of students admitted to the situation is lower than the enrollment plan. In this regard, Zhang Chong suggested that art candidates first focus on the study of cultural courses, the distribution of the proportion should be more than 70% .

Performance Training Organization "King Art Exam" teacher Zhao that the importance of cultural courses should also be at this stage of students' test-preparation strategy. Even if the school exam is cancelled, art students can still get into the art major of the university through the provincial examination or the score line of the culture course.

In addition to cultural courses, training for art majors has also become a problem for students. Recently, an art training institution in Chaoyang District, Beijing, was suspended by the market supervision bureau for operating without permission. Offline training has been called to a halt, the art examination training institutions have also been stalled.

According to Zhao, the organization has been training students since July last year, and students are expected to be at their best in preparation for the exam by February this year. But the delay in the school exam, the state of students will decline due to lack of practice, and not conducive to test preparation. Art Student Wang Fang also told interface education that she wasn't able to practice at home alone after classes were suspended because of a lack of teacher guidance and studio atmosphere.

For Art Examination Training Institutions, highly dependent on offline teaching, online transformation is not easy. Zhao teacher told interface education, the performance of professional pay attention to "table form" (vocal, lines, shape, performance) , only the lines of the class transferred to the line, the remaining three classes are suspended. "Even in a speaking class, the eyes, emotions, and feelings of delivering a line are completely different from the face-to-face experience, " she said.

Zhang Chong told IFE that since most of the professional knowledge of the art examination training has been taught, students should not blindly surf the Internet at this stage, but should weigh how to learn more efficiently. "students can focus on what's going on and think about it, and it's very likely that topics will come up in impromptu commentary, " he said.

The impact of the postponement of the school exam not only affects students, but also challenges the training institutions of the art exam.

Teacher Zhao told interface education that due to the uncertain time of the school exam, training teachers May Face the double pressure of teaching both to new students and to prepare old students for the exam. The workload gets bigger, but the fees don't add up. The agency's recruitment season, originally scheduled for March and April, has also been postponed indefinitely.

In addition, the agency's five-storey storefront in Chaoyang District, Beijing, is vacant. Even during the free period of the art examination in previous years, the venue could be used for performing interest classes or extra-curricular activities. "But now it's just empty and there's nothing to do, " said Ms. Zhao, whose organization had planned to open a franchise in another city this year, but it's unclear whether the plan will work.

Online enrollment hasn't stopped. Zhao said that they are still Weibo, Douyin, art examinees APP for normal recruitment, these channels also ease the business anxiety of offline stores. In addition, the higher unit price of art examination training, students will find information more targeted than other types of training, institutions do not have to worry about online traffic conversion rate.

Affected by the epidemic, information has become the focus of education enterprises. Due to the limitation of space and interaction between teachers and students, art examination training can not be fully online teaching, but online teaching and enrollment promotion will bring new opportunities.

At the request of the interviewees, Zhang Qiong and Wang Fang were given pseudonyms
